The Revival of the Great Leader
London —— It has been two centuries since the Battle of Waterloo, a disastrous defeat for Napoleon that severely damaged French self-esteem. General de Gaulle omitted any mention of the battle entirely when writing about French military history.
Nevertheless, if you acknowledge that "greatness" is a personal quality, then both Napoleon and de Gaulle could be considered the greatest leaders in history.
Marx and Tolstoy would say that there is no such thing as a "great leader" at all.
In Marx's view, the class struggle in France created the environment in which "mediocre and bizarre individuals" like Napoleon could become heroes.
In Tolstoy's view, Napoleon was not an especially outstanding general, and his victories should be attributed to the courage and devotion of the French soldiers who fought in the Battle of Borodino.
Whether or not Napoleon was great, we need to clarify whether the term "great" can be used to describe any leader.
If the answer is yes, then who can be described as great?
The political philosopher Isaiah Berlin believed that great leaders must meet two particularly important criteria.
First of all, can this leader recognize the trends of history?
Otto von Bismarck did, as did his German fellow countryman Konrad Adenauer; borrowing Bismarck's memorable phrase, both heard "the rustling of the mantle of God."
Secondly, did this leader make any significant decisions?
Of course, if a leader is forced to make a decision, he or she should neither be blamed for it nor take credit for it.
Therefore, the key lies in whether the leader has the opportunity to weigh the pros and cons and make the right decisions on behalf of the country.
De Gaulle should therefore be listed among the ranks of any great leaders.
Almost single-handedly, he led France out of the relegation zone after World War II.
After regaining power in 1958, he once again saved his country by suppressing two failed coups, ending the Algerian War, and drafting the Constitution of the Fifth Republic.
Like British Prime Minister Winston Churchill, de Gaulle gave the French a new worldview and established their position in the post-war global order.
In fact, both de Gaulle and Churchill had somewhat excessive final influences in establishing their own nations' worldviews.
Their successors still view the world — and the role their country plays in it — in ways that constrain rational inquiry and distort decision-making, years later.
The result was that the leaders of the two countries afterward were never able to achieve accomplishments that could compare with those of the two great leaders.
But there is still one British prime minister who can be compared to her: Margaret Thatcher, a highly controversial figure, loved by as many people as she was hated by.
Even her resignation 25 years ago stemmed from resistance within her own cabinet and party.
But it is not necessary to win the approval of everyone to become a great leader.
In fact, even Thatcher's critics could not deny her influence.
In addition to being the first female Prime Minister of the United Kingdom and among the earliest female prime ministers in other countries, Thatcher helped reverse Britain's economic decline.
Moreover, her offensive against overly powerful unions enhanced the manageability of the country at a time when it seemed to be sliding into turmoil and chaos.
In light of this, she undeniably has the right to be a candidate for "Great Leader."
Similarly, although far from flawless, Deng Xiaoping of China is also qualified to be regarded as a great leader.
In addition to assisting Mao Zedong in committing atrocities, Deng also played a decisive role in ordering the 1989 Tiananmen Square massacre.
But Deng also revitalized the market, leading China on an unprecedented path of development and prosperity that ultimately lifted hundreds of millions of Chinese people out of poverty.
Many people believe that Lee Kuan Yew, Singapore's founder and long-time prime minister, was highly remarkable, although he might have wished to showcase his talents on a larger stage.
In fact, the size of a country does not seem to affect whether a person can become a great leader.
I certainly had no intention of being disrespectful when I said that a small country like Luxembourg is unlikely to produce great leaders, especially considering that the political atmosphere there is generally not very contentious.
The vast territory of the United States is ample enough to be the birthplace of great leaders.
Some presidents have indeed achieved a great deal.
Harry Truman and Dwight Eisenhower — although not intellectual giants — demonstrated remarkable judgment in establishing the postwar international order that sustained world peace for decades.
Others, including Ronald Reagan and Bill Clinton, possess a high level of talent — the ability to inspire and the art of persuasion.
John F. Kennedy was truly a man of many talents.
He accomplished a great task: defusing the Cuban Missile Crisis.
His inspiring talent was unparalleled; in fact, his assassination after his death solidified the tradition he had left behind.
In South Africa, no one since the death of President Mandela has been regarded as a great figure; Mandela embodied courage, authority, and graceful magnanimity.
In fact, he is the most charming and fascinating leader I have ever met; the other two — former UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan and former U.S. Secretary of State Colin Powell — are either Africans or African Americans.
So what about today?
The only person qualified to claim greatness is Angela Merkel, the de facto leader of the European Union, the German Chancellor.
Like former Chancellor Helmut Kohl, she was often underestimated at first but rarely made mistakes when making important decisions.
Kohl established generous terms for German unification; Merkel opposed Putin during his invasion of Ukraine and adopted a tolerant stance toward the immigration crisis.
I think Marx and Tolstoy are wrong.
Political leaders — the exercisers of political power — can change the situation, for better or worse.
Merkel is today's most obvious example, as she has pointed the way for Europe to deal with a difficult survival crisis.
